{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.11,0.01,0.01,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44088"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1828"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29065"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44088"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of painful swelling in his right groin. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, the patient is in obvious pain. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/62 mmHg, temperature 38.0\u00b0C, respiratory rate 25/min and SpO2 97% on room air. His abdomen is soft with no localising signs. In his right groin there is a tender swelling just superior to the mid-point of the inguinal ligament. There is no discolouration of the overlying skin. The lump does not change with movement or with coughing and is too painful to allow further examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Abdominal CT scan","Fine needle aspiration","Biopsy of lump","Surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis 25-year-old man has presented with acute onset of a painful groin mass. The location of the mass, its tenderness and the abnormal systemic signs, indicate that this is almost certainly a strangulated inguinal hernia and must be considered as such until proven otherwise. This is a surgical emergency, as the strangulated hernia needs to be repaired to avoid infarction of the contents of the hernia. The localised tenderness indicates that there is already an element of ischaemia to the trapped section of bowel. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this man had stable vital signs, and if there was doubt regarding the diagnosis, then an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered. However, in this case ultrasound should not delay surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no role for an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E in the diagnosis of inguinal hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiopsy of lump\u003C/strong\u003E are also not relevant in the diagnosis of inguinal hernias. However, if there was concern about a malignancy, e.g. known penile cancer that may have spread to inguinal lymph nodes, then biopsy may be considered. In such cases the lump would not have been painful or tender.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A strangulated inguinal hernia is a surgical emergency."],"references":["Pastorino A, Alshuqayfi AA. Strangulated Hernia. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555972/","Itani KMF, Fitzgibbons R. Approach to Groin Hernias. JAMA Surgery 2019; 154:551-52."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29065"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29065"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T13:10:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T18:47:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1828"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44088"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"763","links":{"self":"https://app.emed